default4. There is no Capacity Problem on The West Coast defaultMain Linedefault.default4.1 There are four simple tests to help us understand whether there is a capacity problem.
default&#xa0;
default4.2 
defaultSeats Occupied. defaultThe official figures show that WCML Intercity trains are only c59% full at
defaultpeak times (Ref. a).
defaultLower seat loadings than all other domestic long distance routes into any London Terminus.(Ref. b).
default&#xa0;
default4.3 
defaultTrain Configuration.  defaultThere are four first class carriages, which are a third full at peak (Ref. c). 
default&#xa0;
default4.4 
defaultTrain Length. defaultAt present, trains are a mix of 9 and 11 carriages. 12 Carriage trains could be run to all destinations except 
defaultLiverpool
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.5 
defaultTrain Pathsdefault. defaultCould more trains per hour be run at peak times?
defaultRe-engineering 3 pinch points, and introducing In-Cab signalling will increase train speeds and therefore enable there to be more trains per hour.
default&#xa0;
default4.6 51M have shown that by reducing first class carriages to 3 per train and increasing train length to 12 per train, the number of seats per train will be 693, over four times the current average for the route of 164 per train. Network Rail has agreed these figures..
defaultIt more than meets the 
defaultDft’s
default forecast of passengers doubling by 2037.
defaultIn addition by dealing with the 3 
defaultpinchpoints
default on the WCML and implementing In-Cab signalling, extra trains per hour can be run.  
default&#xa0;
default4.7 So the above proves that there is no Intercity Capacity problem.
default&#xa0;
default4.8 Commuter capacity to Milton Keynes and 
defaultNorthampton
default is currently a problem.
default&#xa0;
default4.9 There are simple solutions:
defaultIn the short term allow travellers to Milton Keynes to get off Virgin Trains at 
defaultMilton Keynes
default. Currently the trains stop there but only to pick up passengers.
default default default default defaultIn the medium term spend £260 million on a flyover at 
defaultLedburn
default Junction and use faster commuter trains to increase the number of trains per hour. This could be completed in 5 
defaultyears time
default.
