default6. The numbers quoted by HS2 are grossly incorrect.default6.1 The Financial Times proved that the Peak Time Travel figures were incorrect by 50%.
default&#xa0;
default6.2 Wider benefits of £15 billion are now claimed by HS2. 25 times the value implied in the January 2012 Analysis.
defaultPassenger forecasts include an additional 45,000 return trips daily, generated by the introduction of HS2.
defaultDividing £15 billion by 45,000 and by 300 effective days per annum provides £1,100 for each generated return trip. As only business travel will generate income, that equates to £3,700 per business trip.
defaultWorse still, the benefit of a generated trip is usually only 50% of a pre-existing trip, and therefore each pre-existing  trip is generating £2200, and each pre-existing business trip is generating £7400 per annum. 
defaultMultiply 730 Million round trips per annum (Quoted by Network Rail) by £2,200 and it implies that 
default£1,600 Billion will be generated, which is greater than our Nation’s GDP. (
defaultRef.d
default).
default&#xa0;
default6.3 The most appropriate comparator for 
defaultDft
default passenger forecasts is HS1 which has produced just 38% of its business case forecast; this throws considerable doubt on HS2 forecasts.
default&#xa0;
default6.4 Communication Technology Improvements will reduce the need for business travel.
defaultBritish Telecom Plc. is already demonstrating a very sophisticated version of 3D Conferencing.
default&#xa0;
default6.5 Jobs created by HS2 relate to the construction and maintenance of the HS2 Lines and Rolling Stock, and at Retail Outlets at the new stations. When asked, Birmingham Chamber of Commerce replied they had no idea what sort of additional jobs would be created by HS2.
default&#xa0;
